ce:section.ce:para:
The Huang-Rhys factor provides information about the coupled vibrational modes driving the nonradiative relaxation and about the coupling strengths between electrons and phonons. Hence, it is also referred to as the electron-vibrational spectra (Fig. 6
                        ). This is similar to the influential spectra obtained by Fourier transforming the autocorrelation function of the HOMO-LUMO gap under adiabatic picture (Cui and Xue, 2022). According to Eq. (2), the low-frequency modes are treated classically and influence the nonradiative decay rate through the reorganization energy determined by equation (5), while the high-frequency modes influence the nonradiative decay rates through Huang-Rhys factors. The calculated Huang-Rhys factors (Fig. 6) show that the nonradiative electronic transitions in P-GQDs are mainly coupled to the defect D mode (ca. 1350 cm−1) and the optical G mode (ca. 1650 cm−1) (Ferrari, 2007). These two modes are typically present in graphene materials (Casiraghi et al., 2009). In addition, the nonradiative electronic transitions in GQD-4PO4H2′ and GQD-4P3O2′ are coupled with some lower vibrational modes around the D and G modes. In particular, GQD-4PO2H′ is coupled with significantly more vibrational modes than the other P-functional GQDs. Although GQD-4OPX3′ is coupled with fewer vibrational modes, its electron-phonon coupling strength is much stronger than those of the other systems, as shown by the largest effective Huang-Rhys factor (see Table 1
                        ). In contrast, the effective Huang-Rhys factors in the other molecular systems are almost the same, indicating that their electron-phonon coupling strengths are on the same level.
